<TITLE> Cook leads from the front </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Mar 12 (bdnews24.com)  England completely dominated the first day of the first Test against Bangladesh as they closed on 374-3 at the Zohur Ahmed Chowdhury Stadium in Chittagong on Friday. Skipper Alastair Cook marked his first Test as captain with a composed and stylish unbeaten 158 to make his opposite number Shakib Al Hasan regret choosing to bowl on what proved to be a batman's paradise. It was the left-hander's 11th Test century and he became only the fifth England captain to score three figures on debut. Cook's knock featured 14 fours and two sixes. He reached his hundred in style with a six before tea. The Bangladesh skipper used a total of eight bowlers to try and shackle the tourists. Cook was well supported by Kevin Pietersen, who finally overcame his batting demons with a fluent knock. The pair put on a magnificent 170 runs for the third wicket before dangerman Pietersen was surprised to be bowled for 99 by Abdur Razzak. The only other wickets to fall in the day's play were debutant opener Michael Carberry (30) and Jonathan Trott (39). Carberry was adjudged lbw trying to sweep Mahmudullah with the score on 72 before lunch while Trott was caught behind off a short ball from pacer Rubel Hossain. But replays showed the ball brushed his helmet and made no contact with either glove or bat before going through to the wicketke
